<table width="375" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
<tr valign="top">
	<td>

<div align="right"><a href="javascript:void(playMedia2({w_id:'525920',w:'/library/mlb_!/bb/bbaudio/80lcs/80nlcs_gm3_phihou_radio.wmv',vid:'7808',pid:'bb_audio',cid:'mlb',v:'2'}));"><b><img src="/web/20121026064554im_/http://mlb.mlb.com/images/icons/audio_gold.gif" width="15" height="12" alt="" border="0" align="absmiddle"/> Listen to the radio broadcast</b></a></div>

<b>Starters:</b> Larry Christenson vs. Joe Niekro <br/>
<b>WP:</b> Dave Smith &nbsp; <b>LP:</b> Tug McGraw<br/>

	</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p/>

Although Christenson's five victories that season paled in comparison with Niekro's 20, the two hurlers were nevertheless equally as effective in what turned out to be a terrific pitching duel.  While each allowed a base hit here and there, a combination of great defense, timely double plays and clutch pitching kept either team from sending a runner across the plate.<p/>

An attack keyed by Rose almost led to a Philadelphia run in the third.  With one out, the pesky leadoff hitter singled, then advanced to third on a base hit by <b>Bake McBride</b>.  That brought up Schmidt, whose 48 dingers and 121 RBIs were tops in the league that year.  Schmidt hit it hard, but it was a grounder right at third baseman <b>Enos Cabell</b>.  Cabell easily pegged Rose (who elected to slide, rather than bowl over and injure catcher <b>Luis Pujols</b>, a la his infamous collision with Ray Fosse in the 1970 All-Star Game) at the plate, and a subsequent long fly ball by Luzinski ended the inning.<p/>

In the bottom of the fourth, the Astros took their turn at pressuring Christenson.  With one out, fan favorite <b>Jose Cruz</b> whacked a triple into the right field corner.  <b>Cesar Cedeno</b> also blistered the ball, but it was a grounder that was in shortstop <b>Larry Bowa</b>'s glove before Cruz had a chance to react, so he was forced to hold at third.  Following a walk, Pujols hit an astroturf-induced chopper that had "trouble" written all over it.  But a hustling Schmidt snagged the ball, and his throw in the dirt was scooped up by Rose to squelch the threat.<p/>

Houston nearly ended the contest before it had a chance to go into extra innings.  In the eighth, leadoff man <b>Terry Puhl</b> singled off of reliever <b>Dickie Noles</b>.  Cabell executed a perfect bunt to move him over to second, and with the ever-dangerous <b>Joe Morgan</b> coming to the plate, the Phils called on relief ace <b>Tug McGraw</b>.  The decision almost backfired, as Morgan hit one on the nose and lined a shot to the gap in right center.  But the speedy <b>Gary Maddox</b> made a terrific catch at full gallop, and Puhl was forced to retreat to second.  Two batters later, <b>Dave Bergman</b> flew out to end the inning.<p/>

Meanwhile, Joe Niekro continued to baffle the Phillies with a cunning mix of knucklers and fastballs.  In fact, his command and mastery of the opposition seemed to grow as the game wore on; while he surrendered at least one hit in each of the first four innings, an infield single was the only base hit he permitted from that point on.  When he finally gave way to pinch hitter <b>Gary Woods</b>, he had put ten scoreless innings in the books.<p/>

In the bottom of the eleventh, Morgan came to the plate to face McGraw again.  Morgan had endured a frustrating, injury-filled season, and seen several of his hard-hit balls caught in this contest.  But this time he finally got the upper hand, as he smashed a 1-1 pitch off of the right field wall.  The sore-kneed former MVP easily made it to third, where he was replaced by pinch-runner <b>Rafael Landestoy</b>.<p/>

The Phillies were in a serious hole and they knew it.  With few options, they intentionally walked the next two batters to set up the force play all around and moved all fielders in.  McGraw had to pitch perfectly to get out of this jam, and as magnificent as he had been all year, it was only a matter of time before the hammer dropped.<p/>  

<b>Denny Walling</b> fought off an 0-2 pitch into medium left field.  Luzinski easily caught it, but his subsequent off-line throw wouldn't have nailed Landestoy unless he was sliding into the third base dugout.  Landestoy scored the winning run, and Game 3 of this grueling best-of-five Series was finally won by the scrappy tenants of the Astrodome.<p/>

<span class="textSm">Copyright 1980 by the Office of the Commissioner of Major League Baseball</span><p/>

